al\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Aug 07, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104eio1665702989590.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/eio1665702989590.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/eio1665702989590.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"eio1665702989590\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n               \n PostScript Support\n   </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"eio1665702989590__postscript_support_194454\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Uniface supports output to PostScript files. PostScript files can be directed to a third-party utility for printing or conversion to PDF. This is useful for batch PDF generation, but also provides enhanced printing capabilities on non-Windows platforms.\n </p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"eio1665702989590__p_d64991e1_d64992e1_d64993e1\">The P_X11 device translation table enables PostScript output. (There is also a P_POSTSCRIPT translation table, but it only provides text output, with no support for graphics.) As with all device translation tables, you can copy and edit it to meet your needs, for example, by defining your own device modes to control page size and orientation. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"xiz1665702989085.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/xiz1665702989085.html\" title=\"Printer device tables are a collection of sequences (control codes) associated with specific logical functions (such as bold, form feed, and init). The sequences begin with the escape character and are referred to as escape sequences.\">Device Translation Tables for Printing</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"eio1665702989590__p_d64994e1_d64995e1_d64996e1\">It is possible to configure the fonts used for PostScript printing. On Unix, edit the <code class=\"ph codeph\">[FONTS]</code> section of the <span class=\"ph filepath\">psdef.txt</span> file. On Windows, add a <code class=\"ph codeph\">[postscript]</code> section to your initialization file (<span class=\"ph filepath\">usys.ini</span>).</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"eio1665702989590__p_d64997e1_d64998e1_d64999e1\">It is not possible to print Unicode to PostScript. Only selected European special characters are supported.</p>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/yft1665702989809.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>psdef.txt</a><p>The psdef.txt file is a configuration file for PostScript printing on Unix platforms.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/yzq1665702989739.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>[postscript]</a><p>The [postscript] section of the initialization file defines logical fonts that override those used by default when printing to PostScript on Windows.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2527155\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2527155\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "PostScript Support Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Aug 07, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 PostScript Support Uniface supports output to PostScript files. PostScript files can be directed to a third-party utility for printing or conversion to PDF. This is useful for batch PDF generation, but also provides enhanced printing capabilities on non-Windows platforms. The P_X11 device translation table enables PostScript output. (There is also a P_POSTSCRIPT translation table, but it only provides text output, with no support for graphics.) As with all device translation tables, you can copy and edit it to meet your needs, for example, by defining your own device modes to control page size and orientation. For more information, see Device Translation Tables for Printing . It is possible to configure the fonts used for PostScript printing. On Unix, edit the [FONTS] section of the psdef.txt file. On Windows, add a [postscript] section to your initialization file ( usys.ini ). It is not possible to print Unicode to PostScript. Only selected European special characters are supported. Related Links psdef.txt The psdef.txt file is a configuration file for PostScript printing on Unix platforms. [postscript] The [postscript] section of the initialization file defines logical fonts that override those used by default when printing to PostScript on Windows. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}